04429nam a22007215i 9780813576961DE-B159720210107041344.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210107t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2016012329  a97808135769617 a10.36019/97808135769612doi  a(DE-B1597)526102  a(OCoLC)986403353  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1995.9.S62bC34 2017 4aPN1995.9.S62C34 2016 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4365561 aCagle, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSociology on Film :bPostwar Hollywood's Prestige Commodity /cChris Cagle. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (194 p.) :b15 photographs, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Two Modes of Prestige Film -- t2. Hollywood as Popular Sociology -- t3. Hollywood and the Public Sphere -- t4. A Genre Out of Cycles -- t5. Realist Melodrama -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter World War II, Hollywood’s “social problem films”—tackling topical issues that included racism, crime, mental illness, and drug abuse—were hits with critics and general moviegoers alike. In an era of film famed for its reliance on pop psychology, these movies were a form of popular sociology, bringing the academic discipline’s concerns to a much broader audience. Sociology on Film examines how the postwar “problem film” translated contemporary policy debates and intellectual discussions into cinematic form in order to become one of the preeminent genres of prestige drama. Chris Cagle chronicles how these movies were often politically fractious, the work of progressive directors and screenwriters who drew scrutiny from the House Un-American Activities Committee. Yet he also proposes that the genre helped to construct an abstract discourse of “society” that served to unify a middlebrow American audience. As he considers the many forms of print media that served to inspire social problem films, including journalism, realist novels, and sociological texts, Cagle also explores their distinctive cinematic aesthetics. Through a close analysis of films like Gentleman’s Agreement, The Lost Weekend, and Intruder in the Dust, he presents a compelling case that the visual style of these films was intimately connected to their more expressly political and sociological aspirations. Sociology on Film demonstrates how the social problem picture both shaped and reflected the middle-class viewer’s national self-image, making a lasting impact on Hollywood’s aesthetic direction.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial problems in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357696140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813576961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813576961.jpg  a978-3-11-066614-4  RUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK